name: Elizabeth Warren
bio: US Senator, MA. Fmr teacher & law professor. Wife, mom (Amelia, Alex, Bailey, CFPB), grandmother & Okie. Official campaign account.

social_posts.post_text: I was very happy to endorse Democrats up and down the ticket who fight from the heart for working people—and I’m so glad that these leaders will be serving in federal, state, and local office. Swipe through to see them all. Woo-hoo!
Bruce, Bailey, and I wish you a happy and healthy holiday season!

Even as a young student in my consumer law class, @KatiePorterOC showed a deep-down commitment to making a difference in people’s lives. Since then, she’s taken on Wall Street and giant corporations that cheat families. She delivers. And I’m very happy to endorse her for Senate.
I'm going to fight this every step of the way.

You’ve probably heard about big wins under the Biden-Harris administration like fighting climate change & upgrading infrastructure. Here are a few more ahead of the #StateOfTheUnion—and some that may have flown under your radar. Brought to you by a persistent grassroots movement.

By the way: six years ago today, Mitch McConnell banned me from speaking on the Senate floor after I started reading a letter by Coretta Scott King. He was trying to silence a whole movement. Nevertheless, we persisted. We took back power. And we’re using it to make real change.

My mother’s birthday was Valentine’s Day. We both loved her special connection to the holiday. When I was a girl, I got some heart-shaped pans from the dime store and started baking her a heart-shaped cake every year. I took some time this past weekend to keep up the tradition.

When she was in her 80s, she was in the hospital for some minor surgery. The night before she was scheduled to go home, she said to my daddy, “Don, there's that gas pain again.” Then she died. The autopsy showed she had advanced heart disease—never diagnosed, never treated.

Later, I learned that heart disease is the #1 killer of women. No longer considered just a “man’s disease,” doctors do a much better job screening and treating women for cardiovascular disease today than when my mother had her heart attack.

But because of our health care system, not everyone can get the care they need. So today, I’m remembering my mother, and I’m committed to keeping up the fight for health care as a basic human right.
Snowy morning

We’ve won some big victories for working families in Massachusetts and across the country, but there’s a lot more to do. So today I’m making it official: I’m running for re-election to keep up the fight.

If you’re able to, please pitch in a few bucks at the link in my bio—any amount that makes sense—to help show that our values and plans have strong support. I’d be deeply grateful.

My story doesn’t follow a straight path. I grew up on the ragged edge of the middle class. After my daddy’s heart attack, my family came within an inch from losing our house, but my mother got a minimum wage job at Sears that saved our family.

I dropped out of college at 19 to get married, but got a second chance at a public college that cost $50 a semester and got to live my dream of becoming a public school teacher.

I’ve dedicated my career to studying why families go broke and fighting to rebuild the middle class. After Wall Street crashed our economy, I fought to create the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau, which has already returned about $16 billion to Americans who’ve been cheated.

I first ran for Senate to tax greedy corporations, to invest in jobs and our infrastructure, and to rein in student loan companies. And guess what? We got it all done.

But the fight to make our government work for everyone—not just the wealthy and well-connected—isn’t over. So I’m running for re-election. Can you make a contribution of $5 or whatever you can today and become a Founding Donor of this campaign? Click the link in my bio to chip in.
I’m in this fight to put our government on the side of working families. Join our re-election campaign today at the link in my bio.
Let’s stay in touch—text TEAM to 244-77, and help build our re-election campaign from the ground up.
I LOVE getting to speak with the people who make our grassroots campaign possible. Pitch in any amount, and I might call you to say thanks! Click the link in my bio.

Here’s a message from me and Bailey ahead of tonight’s big fundraising deadline. A contribution of any kind will show that our values have strong support—can you pitch in? Click on the link in my bio.

Next Wednesday, I’m hosting the first Town Hall of our re-election campaign—with special guests @Maura_Healey, @AyannaPressley, and @WuTrain. Will we see you in Roxbury? Click the link in my bio to RSVP.

Thank you, Roxbury, for a great conversation on how we can make our government work for everyone, not just a thin slice at the top. And thank you to @Maura_Healey, @WuTrain, @AyannaPressley, and @Ruthzee4Boston for joining our Town Hall.
The birthday boy gets a burrito

First, you identify the problem. Then, you fight to fix it—for as long as it takes. Take a look at this timeline of how I’ve been working—and will continue to work—to deliver relief to people getting crushed by student debt:
Here’s how we won a crackdown on wealthy tax cheats and made progress towards fast, free tax filing for all Americans:

This month, as I prepared to deliver commencement speeches for graduation season, I turned to some of you to share your best wisdom for members of the class of 2023 as they start their next chapters. 

I received so many kind and thoughtful submissions, and here were a few that stood out to me. I think, no matter our age, we could all take some of this advice with us. 

I hope you’ll share with a recent (or soon-to-be!) graduate in your life.
I’m very happy to be holding a Town Hall in Holyoke on Sunday, June 25, and I’d love to see you there! Click the link in my bio for more details and to RSVP.

The rain couldn’t stop this weekend’s Juneteenth celebration and Roxbury Homecoming in Franklin Park! Honored to join my friend and partner @Ruthzee4Boston for this reminder of the power of building community as we work for racial justice.

Thank you to my sweetie, Bruce, for such a wonderful cake (Bailey enjoyed it, too), and thank you all for the well wishes today! Looking forward to another year of fighting for families in Massachusetts and across the country.

One year ago today, the Supreme Court overturned Roe v. Wade. If you’re still angry and determined to fight back, can you click the link in my bio and split a donation between @OhioansForReproFreedom and @FLProtectFree? Help them pass state constitutional amendments protecting reproductive freedom.

When reproductive freedom is on the ballot, reproductive freedom wins—remember last year’s victories in Kansas, Michigan, and Kentucky? So let’s build on those successes in Ohio and Florida. 

I won’t stop working to codify Roe at the federal level and ensure the right to an abortion nationwide—because the government shouldn’t be interfering with people’s personal medical decisions. Today’s awful anniversary calls on us to stay in the fight.

Pride is a celebration—and a statement of resilient defiance. I was very glad to join North Shore Pride this weekend with my friend @KimDriscollMA, and I’ll keep fighting for full LGBTQ+ equality so everyone can live proudly and safely as themselves.

You don’t get what you don’t fight for. Here’s the inside story of how we beat back a giant monopoly, lowered the cost of hearing aids by thousands of dollars, and scored a win for millions of Americans.
This fight is not over.
When we get organized and get in the fight, we can beat back powerful special interests and make real change. Here’s how we achieved the biggest advance in corporate tax fairness in three decades:
Had this waiting for me after a busy day yesterday—my sweetie always remembers. Happy 43rd anniversary, Bruce!

Wishing a very happy birthday to the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau! We’ve got so many reasons to celebrate.

@JoeBiden and @KamalaHarris are putting money back in working people’s pockets and fighting to protect our freedoms. Let’s do everything we can to keep them in the White House and help them finish the job.

For the sake of our national security, crypto firms should have to follow the same anti-money-laundering rules as other financial institutions. And I’ve got a bipartisan bill to make it happen.
